### 7.4 Differentiation by first principles

The gradient at any point on the curve is defined as the gradient of the tangent at that point on the curve.

Consider a curve \(y=\mathbb{f}(x)\). Let \(P(x,\,y)\) be an arbitrary fixed point chosen on the curve. Our objective is to find the gradient of the curve at \(P\).

Let \(Q(x+\bar{\alpha},y+\bar{\delta}y)\) be another point on the curve near \(P\) where \(\bar{\alpha}x\) (read as 'delta x') denotes the small increment of \(x\) and \(\bar{\delta}y\) (delta y) denotes the corresponding small increment of \(y\).

The gradient of the chord \(PQ=\frac{\delta y}{\delta x}\).

Now imagine \(Q\) to be a "bead" threaded to the curve and is gradually sliding down towards \(P\).

As \(Q\) approaches \(P\), we see that the gradient of the chord \(PQ\) approaches the gradient of the tangent to the curve at \(P\).

Gradient of the curve at \(P=\lim\limits_{Q\to P}\left(\text{gradient of the chord }PQ\right)\)

\[=\lim\limits_{\delta x\to 0}\frac{\delta y}{\delta x}\,\,\left(\text{since }Q \to P\,\,\text{ as }\,\,\bar{\alpha}x\to 0\right)\]

Since \(\delta y=\mathbb{f}(x+\delta x)-\mathbb{f}(x)\), the gradient of tangent at \(P\) is

\[\boxed{\lim\limits_{\delta x\to 0}\frac{\delta y}{\delta x}=\lim\limits_{ \delta x\to 0}\frac{\mathbb{f}(x+\delta x)-\mathbb{f}(x)}{\delta x}}\]

This process of taking the limit of \(\frac{\delta y}{\delta x}\) as \(\delta x\to 0\) to find the gradient of the tangent at a point on the curve is known as differentiation by first principles.

The symbol '\(\frac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}\)' is used to denote the more cumbersome notation \(\lim\limits_{\delta x\to 0}\frac{\delta y}{\delta x}\), i.e. \(\frac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}=\lim\limits_{\delta x\to 0}\frac{\delta y}{\delta x}\)

The symbol '\(\frac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}\)' is called the derivative of \(y\) with respect to \(x\) or equivalently, the gradient function corresponding to the curve \(y=\mathbb{f}(x)\).

**Remarks:**

1. If \(y=\mathds{f}(x)\), we can also denote \(\frac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}\) by \(\mathrm{f}^{\prime}\big{(}x\big{)}\) (read as 'fprime of \(x\)').
2. '\(\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}\)' is an operator, not a fraction. \(\frac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}\) is read as 'the result when \(\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}\) operates on \(y\)' or 'differentiate \(y\) with respect to \(x\)'.

