### Implicit Differentiation

Suppose we are given \(y=\mbox{f}(x)\). Then to find \(\frac{\mbox{d}\nu}{\mbox{d}x}\), we simply differentiate \(\mbox{f}(x)\) directly. However, there are instances when \(y\) cannot be written explicitly as a function of \(x\). In this case, \(y\) is said to be an **implicit function** of \(x\). In such cases, we will use the **chain rule** to find \(\frac{\mbox{d}\nu}{\mbox{d}x}\). This process is known as **implicit differentiation.** So to differentiate a function in \(y\) with respect to \(x\), we have \(\frac{\mbox{d}}{\mbox{d}x}\big{[}\mbox{g}(y)\big{]}=\frac{\mbox{d} \mbox{g}(y)}{\mbox{d}y}\frac{\mbox{d}\nu}{\mbox{d}x}\). For example \(\frac{\mbox{d}}{\mbox{d}x}\,y^{2}=\frac{\mbox{d}}{\mbox{d}y}(y^{2})\frac{\mbox {d}\nu}{\mbox{d}x}=2y\frac{\mbox{d}y}{\mbox{d}x}\).

To obtain the derivative of an implicit function, **differentiate** the given equation **term by term** with respect to the variable required.

