## 8 The Gradient Function

Let \(y=\mathsf{f}(x)\,,\) then \(\,y=\mathsf{f}^{\prime}(x)\,\) where \(\,\mathsf{f}^{\prime}(x)=\frac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}\,\) is called the **gradient function** of \(y=\mathsf{f}(x)\). \(\,y=\mathsf{f}^{\prime}(x)\,\) is the function whose value at \(x\) is the slope or gradient of the tangent line to the graph of \(y=\mathsf{f}(x)\,\) at \(x\).

### Interpretation of \(\,\mathsf{f}^{\prime}(x)>0\,\)and \(\,\mathsf{f}^{\prime}(x)<0\,\)

Algebraically, a function \(\mathsf{f}\) is said to be **strictly increasing** on a domain \(D\) if for all \(\,x_{1},x_{2}\in D\,\), \(\,x_{1}<x_{2}\,\Rightarrow\mathsf{f}\big{(}x_{1}\big{)}<\mathsf{f}\big{(}x_{2 }\big{)}\,.\) Similarly, a function \(\mathsf{f}\) is said to be **strictly decreasing** on a domain \(D\) if for all \(\,x_{1},x_{2}\in D\,,\,\,x_{1}<x_{2}\,\Rightarrow\mathsf{f}\big{(}x_{1}\big{)} >\mathsf{f}\big{(}x_{2}\big{)}\,.\)

Consider a function given by \(y=\mathsf{f}(x)\).

If \(\,\frac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}>0\,\) for \(\,a<x<b\), then \(\,y=\mathsf{f}(x)\,\) is **strictly increasing** for \(\,a<x<b\).

If \(\,\frac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}<0\,\) for \(\,a<x<b\), then \(\,y=\mathsf{f}(x)\,\) is **strictly decreasing** for \(\,a<x<b\).

