### Stationary Points

A point \((a,\,\mathrm{f}(a))\) on the graph of \(y=\mathrm{f}(x)\) is called a **stationary point** if \(\frac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}x}=0\) at that point. In other words, \(\mathrm{f}^{\prime}\left(a\right)=0\). The value of \(\mathrm{f}(a)\) is called the **stationary value** at this stationary point \((a,\,\mathrm{f}(a))\).

#### 8.2.1 Nature of Stationary Points

**(a)**: **Turning Points**

Turning points are either maximum points or minimum points.

A **maximum** point on a curve is a stationary point at which the \(y\)-coordinate is greater than the \(y\)-coordinates of any other points on the curve in the neighbourhood of the point.

A **minimum** point on a curve is a stationary point at which the \(y\)-coordinate is smaller than the \(y\)-coordinates of any other points on the curve in the neighbourhood of the point.

**(b)**: **Stationary Points of Inflexion**

A **stationary point of inflexion** is a point with zero gradient and the curvature of the curve changes in the neighbourhood of the stationary point.

