### Derivative as a Rate of change

Suppose that a particle is moving along a straight line so that we know its position \(s\), relative to a fixed point \(O\) on the line, as a function of time \(t\) : \(s=\mathrm{f}(t)\). That is, the function \(\mathrm{f}(t)\) tells us its position from point \(O\) at any time \(t\). This is the **displacement** of the particle at time \(t\). The rate at which a particle's displacement changes is called the **velocity** of the particle. Then, if a particle's displacement at time \(t\) is \(s=\mathrm{f}(t)\), then the particle's velocity **(instantaneous velocity)** at time \(t\) is the derivative of displacement with respect to time, that is, \(\nu(t)=\frac{\mathrm{d}x}{\mathrm{d}t}\). Similarly, the rate at which a particle's velocity changes is called the **acceleration** of the particle. The acceleration measures how quickly the particle picks up or loses speed. If a particle's position at time \(t\) is \(s=\mathrm{f}(t)\), then the particle's acceleration at time \(t\) is the derivative of velocity with respect to time, that is, \(a(t)=\frac{\mathrm{d}\nu}{\mathrm{d}t}=\frac{\mathrm{d}^{\prime}s}{\mathrm{d}t}\).

