**Annex: A short note about locus**

A locus is a path formed by a moving point which moves according to certain conditions.

**Example 1**: The locus of a point \(P\) moves so that it is always a same distance \(r\) from a fixed point \(C\left(h,\,k\right)\). What shape is it? Find its Cartesian equation.

**Solution**:

Obviously, it is a circle. The centre is the point \(C\) and the radius is \(r\).

To find the Cartesian equation of the locus of a moving point, we always let the coordinates of the moving point \(P\) be \(\left(x,y\right)\), then we have

\[CP=r \Rightarrow \sqrt{\left(x-h\right)^{2}+\left(y-k\right)^{2}}=r\] \[\Rightarrow \left(x-h\right)^{2}+\left(y-k\right)^{2}=r^{2}\]

**Example 2**: The locus of a point which moves so that it is an equal distance from two points, \(A\left(a,\,b\right)\) and \(B\left(c,\,d\right)\).

What shape is it? Find its Cartesian equation.

Solution:

It is a straight line. In fact, it is the perpendicular bisector of the line joining \(A\) and \(B\). To find the Cartesian equation of the locus, we let the coordinates of the moving point \(P\) be \(\left(x,y\right)\), then,

\[PA=PB \Rightarrow \sqrt{\left(x-a\right)^{2}+\left(y-b\right)^{2}}=\sqrt{\left(x-c \right)^{2}+\left(y-d\right)^{2}}\] \[\Rightarrow \left(x-a\right)^{2}+\left(y-b\right)^{2}=\left(x-c\right)^{2}+ \left(y-d\right)^{2}\] \[\Rightarrow \left[\left(x-a\right)-\left(x-c\right)\right]\left[\left(x-a \right)+\left(x-c\right)\right]=\left[\left(y-d\right)-\left(y-b\right)\right] \left[\left(y-d\right)+\left(y-b\right)\right]\] \[\Rightarrow \left(c-a\right)\left(2x-a-c\right)=\left(b-d\right)\left(2y-b-d\right)\] \[\Rightarrow 2y-b-d=\frac{c-a}{b-d}\left(2x-a-c\right)=\frac{2\left(c-a \right)x}{b-d}-\frac{\left(c-a\right)\left(a+c\right)}{b-d}\] \[\Rightarrow y=\frac{c-a}{b-d}x-\frac{a+c}{2}\left(\frac{c-a}{b-d}\right)+ \frac{b+d}{2}\] \[\Rightarrow y=\frac{c-a}{b-d}x-\frac{c^{2}-a^{2}}{2\left(b-d\right)}+ \frac{\left(b+d\right)\left(b-d\right)}{2\left(b-d\right)}\] \[\Rightarrow y=\frac{c-a}{b-d}x-\frac{c^{2}-a^{2}-b^{2}+d^{2}}{2\left(b-d \right)}\quad\quad....\left(\text{I}\right)\]

It is an equation for a straight line.

Now, we want to prove that this locus is the perpendicular bisector of the line \(AB\).

Proof:

\[\text{Gradient of }AB\text{ is }\frac{d-b}{c-a}.\] \[\text{Gradient of the locus }=-\frac{c-a}{d-b}.\] \[\text{Since }\frac{d-b}{c-a}\times\left[-\frac{c-a}{d-b}\right]=-1\]

The locus is perpendicular to the line joining \(A\) and \(B\).

Hence the locus is a perpendicular bisector of the line joining \(A\) and \(B\).

